'''Summon nasties''' is a [[monster spell]] that appears in ''[[NetHack]]''.

{{todo|List more variant changes.}}

==Description==
Summon nasties is a non-directed spell that can be used by any [[monster]] of at least [[Monster level|level]] 16 with the ability to cast [[mage spell]]s.{{refsrc|src/mcastu.c|19|version=NetHack 3.6.7}}{{refsrc|src/mcastu.c|105|version=NetHack 3.6.7}}{{refsrc|src/mcastu.c|736|version=NetHack 3.6.7}} The spell is only used by hostile monsters against the [[hero]], and they will only use it if they at least think the character is nearby.{{refsrc|src/mcastu.c|782|version=NetHack 3.6.7}}{{refsrc|src/mcastu.c|802|version=NetHack 3.6.7}}

When cast, a number of hostile monsters will be generated around the [[hero]]'s position, which can be affected by [[displacement]] or [[invisibility]] depending on the caster.{{refsrc|src/mcastu.c|417|version=NetHack 3.6.7}}{{refsrc|src/mcastu.c|420|version=NetHack 3.6.7}} These monsters are selected from a list of [[#Nasties|nasties]], and are created until either [[D notation|d]]({{sfrac|XLvl|3}}) nasties that are either neutral or co-aligned with the summoner have been created, or the maximum number of 10 nasties have been created - in practice, it is possible for [[group]]s of monsters to be generated among the summoned nasties and result in a total higher than 10, and spellcasting monsters of an alignment that has fewer co-aligned nasties will summon more nasties on average.{{refsrc|src/wizard.c|22|version=NetHack 3.6.7}}{{refsrc|src/wizard.c|29|version=NetHack 3.6.7}}{{refsrc|src/wizard.c|568|version=NetHack 3.6.7}}

If this spell is cast in [[Gehennom]], it is treated as if the [[Wizard of Yendor]] is summoning regardless of the caster, and there is a {{frac|10}} chance that a [[major demon]] is summoned - this can include a [[demon lord]] or [[demon prince]].{{refsrc|src/wizard.c|556|nethack=3.6.7}} Both this and the remote summoning performed by the Wizard of Yendor are considered neutral for this purpose.

Monsters summoned by the spell respect [[genocide]], but not [[extinction]]: If a genocided monster would be summoned, it is replaced by an ordinary random monster (which is not guaranteed to be hostile). Summoned monsters will be unable to use special attacks such as monster spells or breath weapons for up to 4 turns.{{refsrc|src/wizard.c|613|version=NetHack 3.6.7}} To partially curtail "summon storms", summoned spellcasters will have a lower [[Monster difficulty|difficulty]] than the caster unless they replace a genocided monster, and [[titan]]s, [[ki-rin]] and [[golden naga]]s are excluded.{{refsrc|src/wizard.c|45|version=NetHack 3.6.7}}{{refsrc|src/wizard.c|585|version=NetHack 3.6.7}} Monsters of the [[Demon (monster class)|demon]] [[monster class]] will never summon [[angelic being]]s, and vice versa.{{refsrc|src/wizard.c|596|version=NetHack 3.6.7}} If cast on the [[Rogue level]], nasties not represented by an uppercase letter are less likely to be summoned.{{refsrc|src/wizard.c|526|version=NetHack 3.6.7}}

{{upcoming|NetHack 3.7.0|Spellcasters casting summon nasties can no longer summon monsters of equal or higher difficulty than themselves. Thus, Archons cannot summon more Archons, arch-liches cannot summon more arch-liches, and so on.

If a genocided monster with a pre-grown form (that is not explicitly a baby form) is chosen, and this form is not also genocided, it will appear in place of the genocided monster. For example, mind flayers can appear in place of genocided master mind flayers. This also happens if the chosen nasty is inappropriate for the location, such as an arch-lich outside Gehennom.

Per {{commit|3eed500}}, when the difficulty is high enough to summon arch-liches or Archons (e.g., the Wizard casting it or via random harassment), at most one arch-lich OR one Archon will be created by a single casting of summon nasties.}}

